data.content:
Replace `[ExpectedException]` with `Assert.ThrowsException<T>`, which is more precise — it pinpoints exactly which line should throw:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()
{
    var service = new UserService();

    Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(
        () => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));
}
```

**Why this is better:**
- `[ExpectedException]` passes if *any* line throws, masking bugs (e.g., the constructor throwing instead of `CreateUser`).
- `Assert.ThrowsException` scopes the assertion to the exact call.
- You can also capture the exception to assert on its message:

```csharp
var ex = Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(
    () => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));
Assert.AreEqual("email", ex.ParamName);
```

> **MSTest v4 note:** If you're on MSTest v4+, use `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>` instead — `ThrowsException` was renamed, and `[ExpectedException]` was removed entirely.
